<Document>
<name>North Coast 500 — West &amp; North</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>North Coast 500 — West &amp; North</h2><p><i>Scotland · Highland, Inverness to Thurso via Applecross, Ullapool, and Durness</i></p><p><b>The wild west and north of the British Isles' most remote driving — single-track roads, deserted beaches, the highest pass in the UK.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>369 km (229 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>3–4 days minimum</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>May–September (May has long light and few midges; midges peak Jun–Aug)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Single-track road etiquette (use passing places, never stop in them); midges; sheep on road; tourist traffic in summer; Bealach na Bà has 20% gradients and is closed to caravans</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>749</td></tr></table><hr><p>The North Coast 500 was promoted as a tourism brand in 2015, lacing together pre-existing roads into an 830 km loop from Inverness. The west and north sections are the wild ones — single-track tarmac unspooling between mountains and sea, with passing places every couple of hundred metres and Highland cattle as the regular traffic obstruction. The Bealach na Bà over to Applecross is the steepest road in the UK, with gradients to 20% and hairpins like nowhere else in Britain. North of Ullapool the landscape becomes truly empty — Suilven and Stac Pollaidh erupt out of bog like Patagonian peaks. At Cape Wrath the British Isles end.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Bealach na Bà</b> — 'Pass of the Cattle' — the highest road in the UK at 626 m and the country's only true alpine-style pass with switchbacks. Caravans banned. In fog or wind, save it for another day.</li><li><b>Applecross</b> — Gaelic-speaking village of A' Chomraich. Applecross Inn does the seafood the Highlands are famous for. The view across to Skye at sunset is the cover of every Scottish tourism brochure.</li><li><b>Torridon</b> — Surrounded by some of the oldest mountains in Europe — Liathach and Beinn Eighe are ~750 million-year-old Torridonian sandstone, with white quartzite caps glinting in sun.</li><li><b>Ullapool</b> — Planned 18th-century herring-fishing town, now ferry port to the Outer Hebrides. The Ceilidh Place hosts excellent live folk music.</li><li><b>Lochinver / Suilven</b> — Suilven is a 731 m sandstone monolith that erupts from a treeless bog — it looks like nothing else in Britain. The hike is 22 km return; it's worth a day.</li><li><b>Durness / Smoo Cave</b> — Vast sea cave you can walk into; an underground waterfall thunders inside. Ceannabeinne Beach a few km east is white sand and turquoise water — Britain's accidental Caribbean.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
